Observation Details: At least 6 along Red Road between 5:30 and 6:00.  Saw 6 birds on road (or their eye shine).  Heard 2 birds singing as it was getting light that I believe were additional birds.  I did not play a tape, but a couple of birds flew in towards me.  Perhaps attracted by my light?  It was interesting seeing a pair of glowing eyes flying towards me.  They did not appear concerned with my presence, my light, or the flash from my camera.  They would fly-catch right in front of me sometimes landing about 10 feet away.

Observation Details: Saw a robin-size all red bird fly across the road in front of me and down the hill.  I figured it was either a Cardinal, a Summer Tanager, or I was hallucinating from dehydration. I figured the latter was more likely.  After waiting around a bit, I spotted a male Summer Tanager sitting in a dead oak below me.  It was all red with a pale tanager-shaped bill.    The coordinates where the tanager flew across the road are: (37.8727258, -121.9175456).  It is where Green Ranch Road has a sharp bend, and there is a lot of lush, shaded vegetation and deciduous trees with some running water. Just the kind of place I would want to hang out if I were a lost Summer Tanager.

As it got dark, they hunkered down and blended into the ground.  They appeared to have come to spend the night.  Tide was half way between low and high, probably around 4 ft.  Came back the next morning around 8:00, and there was not a single peep.

Breeding plumage adult sitting on the water near Brook’s Island.  Relative size of bird and bill looked too small for a Laughing Gull.  When it spread it’s wings, could tell it was not a Bonaparte’s.  Bird then got up and with great luck flew directly over my head. Got good looks at the wing tips with strong white patterning on the tips and also white separating the black on the tips from the rest of the wing. Unfortunately, I did not get a picture of the flying bird.  After flying over my head, it appeared to fly off in the direction of Miller Knox.  Update: Ethan Monk notified me that the same bird was likely seen a couple hours later at Fort Baker in Marin County by Derek Lecy  https://ebird.org/checklist/S71401152

The faces of the Wilson’s appeared to be of more uniformed coloration due to the lack of a black eye patch.  The backs of the Wilson’s appeared to be of a lighter, more uniformed gray coloration than the Red-necked.

Observation Details: Breeding plumage adult sitting on the water near Brook’s Island.  Relative size of bird and bill looked too small for a Laughing Gull.  When it spread it’s wings, could tell it was not a Bonaparte’s.  Bird then got up and with great luck flew directly over my head. Got good looks at the wing tips with strong white patterning on the tips and also white separating the black on the tips from the rest of the wing. Unfortunately, I did not get a picture of the flying bird.  After flying over my head, it appeared to fly off in the direction of Miller Knox.  Update: Ethan Monk notified me that the same bird was likely seen a couple hours later at Fort Baker in Marin County by Derek Lecy  https://ebird.org/checklist/S71401152

Circled overhead in good light for about 2 minutes.  Had good looks.  Could see that they were large swifts that were black below with the primaries and secondaries appearing to be lighter in color, a grayish black.  Sometimes would spread their tails which also at times appeared slightly notched.  Very poor photos show that the shape is that of a swift and that the shape is not that of a Vaux’s Swift nor a Purple Martin.  The photos also show that there is no white underneath ruling out White-throated Swifts.

Initially seen catching insects over the slough on the east side of the island.  It then perched facing us relatively close for a few seconds.  It's dark charcoal gray head and chest with a contrasting white chin made us immediately think it was a Cassin's.  The head was much darker gray than is typically seen on a Western Kingbird.  The bird then flew down off the levee to a fence behind a locked gate.  John made careful field observations through his scope while I made feeble attempts at taking pictures.  While the pictures are blurry, they show the key field marks that were seen in the field.  Specifically, the dark charcoal gray head and chest contrasting with the white chin.   From John's scope views of the bird flying and spreading its tail, there were definitely no white outer tail feathers.  Despite the clear views of the tail, the pale tip that is often seen on Cassin's was not visible.  Through the scope, the color of the tail was more of a dark brown as opposed to the jet black of a Western Kingbird.

Observation Details: Found by John Toldi.  Plump, gray shorebirds same size as accompanying Black Turnstones.  Turnstones black, Surfbirds gray.  Surfbirds definitely lighter in comparison to Turnstones.  Yellow legs obvious.  Mostly roosting, but when spread wings and/or flew, solid gray back contrasted with a white upper tail / rump followed by a strong black band on tip of tail.  White stripes on wings.  Two clumps/flocks near the end of the rock jetty that comes down from Brooks Island. Distant scope views from Ferry Point.  Tide moderately high.

What appears to be a vertical black carpal bar is puzzling.  With a Common, I would expect to see a horizontal bar with it possibly transitioning to a vertical bar.  A vertical bar by itself seems strange.  The second picture of the same bird does not show a bar.  Did the bird re-arrange its feathers to hide it, or was the bar in the first picture a shadow?  The tern was quite far away and the bar was not readily visible in the field.  The other interesting feature of this tern is the grayish underside contrasting with the white chin and upper chest.  This is a feature of the Common Tern.  This feature on this bird can be compared/contrasted to the Forster's Tern on this checklist that was standing nearby.  The lighting was the same, but the underside is clearly whiter with the contrast between the white underside and gray wing particularly noticeable on the Forster's.    Addendum: Went back the next day and found what we believe was the same tern.  We got somewhat closer and had better light.  Neither the dark carpal bar nor the grayish underside were visible on the bird.  We also had a chance to observe what I believe was the same bird in flight and it was totally characteristic of a Forster's.  Assuming that the bird pictured here is the same as the bird seen and photographed the next day (see checklist), then this bird is a Forster's with lighting that led to unusual shading.  I would welcome thoughts/comments on this bird.  raffelrobert@gmail.com

(37.8214957, -121.6414163)  The Tricoloreds would frequently sit on the fence near the cattails.  All appeared to be male, although there was 1 female that I could not identify for sure.  They were also seen feeding on the hillside beyond the fence.  They would go into the cattails and disappear.  There were a couple of Red-winged Blackbirds sharing the area as well as 4 or 5 Brewer's.  Initially thought they might be breeding in the cattails, however, when I returned on 5/2/20 to check the location again, there were no Tricolored's.   The two most likely scenarios that come to mind are: 1) the Tricoloreds were just checking the location out, but found it unsuitable, 2) they finished breeding by 5/2 and had moved out.  The landowner from nearby spoke with me.  He was very concerned about "environmentalists" messing up his land.  Nevertheless, he was pleasant/civil.

Observation Details: A flock of about a dozen birds, maybe a few more.  Originally found by Teri & Chris Willis on December 5th.  The flock was along the EBMUD Trail about half way between Hookston Rd and Astrid Dr.  The flock would feed on the ground and then fly up into the trees when people passed by and then returned to forage on the ground.  Some appeared to lack the dark line through the lores but had gray rumps.

Great find by Jim Chiropolos this morning, and thank you to Teale Fristoe for providing me with directions.  To get to the location where the sapsucker was seen, park at the Skyline Gate Staging Area.  Then head out of the Northeast corner of the parking lot along East Ridge Trail.  After about .2 miles, take the Phillips Loop trail to the right.  Go about another .2 miles and the trail splits.  The main trail continues downhill, but there is a distinct, but less travelled trail that heads up to the left.  50 yards or so up the trail to the left there is a shrubby tree with red berries combined with a shrubby bay-type tree.  The sapsucker was hanging out there.  Approximate coordinates are: 37.831208, -122.179982    I took a number pictures from multiple angles in an attempt to decipher this bird.  There seems to be consensus that it is a hybrid.  The extensive red on the top of the head as well as the slight red under the black breast band seem to indicate that Red-breasted Sapsucker is part of the mix.  I am struggling with whether the remainder of the bird is a Red-naped or Yellow-bellied Sapsucker.  The strong, solid black malar stripe that goes from the bill down to the breast band is characteristic of a Yellow-bellied, however, this bird seems like a close match to the cover photo on the Shunk article for a Red-naped x Red-breasted. http://www.woodpeckerwonderland.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/Shunk-2005-Sapsucker-Hybrids.pdf  I would be interested in what others think.  I can be reached at raffelrobert@gmail.com

Locality: Mount Diablo State Park - Green Ranch Road, Clayton US-CA (37.8702,-121.9250)
Observation Details: Saw a robin-size all red bird fly across the road in front of me and down the hill.  I figured it was either a Cardinal, a Summer Tanager, or I was hallucinating from dehydration. I figured the latter was more likely.  After waiting around a bit, I spotted a male Summer Tanager sitting in a dead oak below me.  It was all red with a pale tanager-shaped bill.    The coordinates where the tanager flew across the road are: (37.8727258, -121.9175456).  It is where Green Ranch Road has a sharp bend, and there is a lot of lush, shaded vegetation and deciduous trees with some running water. Just the kind of place I would want to hang out if I were a lost Summer Tanager.

Bird flew overhead while I was watching my son's soccer game. On flyover, belly appeared unusually yellow.  Landed high in the trees above the community center next the pond with the fountain.  It remained there about 4 minutes and flew off.  Too far away to get a good look with binoculars.  Looking at pictures of perched bird, noticed large bill, greenish back, yellow on breast extends up high to chin, and a notched tail.  Given that this identification was a little more challenging than most, I would welcome feedback at raffelrobert@gmail.com

Observation Details: Confirmed by hummingbird bander - Susan Campbell, Southern Pines, NC Also, in "Hummingbirds of North America", it says, " 30% of adult female Allens's show distinct to extensive rufous edgings on their uppertail coverts, versus narrow to absent edgings on adult femal Rufous.  Thus, extensive rufous on the uppertail-coverts is strongly indicative of Allen's."  This trait appears to be visible in these pictures.
